webpackJsonp([0xceb78fd0184e],{404:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{contentfulBlogPost:{title:"Udacity Android course. Recap",slug:"udacity-android-course-recap",publishDate:"1458334800000",content:[{__typename:"ContentfulBlogPostCopy",id:"c2sGwx11IgsE4eoeiWkkY6s",copy:{childMarkdownRemark:{html:'<p>How’s it going?</p>\n<p>I was going to write this post last <em>two months</em>, but today is the day I have time and intention to write this post.</p>\n<p>About two months ago, when I was on my winter holidays, I passed a course on <a href="https://udacity.com/">Udacity</a>, called <em>Developing Android Apps</em> built by Google. The couse level is <em>intermediate</em>, and time needed to pass is ten weeks, assuming 6 hours per week. But I finished it in about 10 days.</p>'}}},{__typename:"ContentfulBlogPostImage",id:"c9EQCFdaoGkSMU2ymwmCYI",caption:null,image:{resolutions:{src:"//images.ctfassets.net/w1fxlmsi3y1l/lIfNwoY73a24AsoWqym4k/b6b8ae941a8f29dc9ec925f9d23195a3/udacity_android_course.png?w=400&q=100",srcSet:"//images.ctfassets.net/w1fxlmsi3y1l/lIfNwoY73a24AsoWqym4k/b6b8ae941a8f29dc9ec925f9d23195a3/udacity_android_course.png?w=400&h=225&q=100 1x,\n//images.ctfassets.net/w1fxlmsi3y1l/lIfNwoY73a24AsoWqym4k/b6b8ae941a8f29dc9ec925f9d23195a3/udacity_android_course.png?w=600&h=337&q=100 1.5x,\n//images.ctfassets.net/w1fxlmsi3y1l/lIfNwoY73a24AsoWqym4k/b6b8ae941a8f29dc9ec925f9d23195a3/udacity_android_course.png?w=800&h=450&q=100 2x,\n//images.ctfassets.net/w1fxlmsi3y1l/lIfNwoY73a24AsoWqym4k/b6b8ae941a8f29dc9ec925f9d23195a3/udacity_android_course.png?w=1200&h=675&q=100 3x"}}},{__typename:"ContentfulBlogPostCopy",id:"c4jnnqMLf04cus6Aik8Gow6",copy:{childMarkdownRemark:{html:'<p>Here in this post, I want to <em>conclude</em> what I have done and learned throughout this course. Actually, I was writing what I have learned in each big commit, in my <a href="https://github.com/aibolik/Sunshine">GitHub repo for this course</a>.</p>\n<p>By the end of the course, we had a built application called Sunshine, that uses <em>Android’s best practices</em>.</p>\n<p>Why to choose Sunshine? Because it has all functionality that more advanced application has, and we can see in practice many APIs, where and how they are used.</p>\n<p>So, what I have learned new for me:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Implementing <em>Settings(Preferences) Activity</em> without imlpementing any UI</li>\n<li>Using Fragments in two pane mode</li>\n<li><em>The most important thing I learned, Android Best Practice for Database Implementation(Using Contract-DbHelper- Provider scheme)</em></li>\n<li>And the <em>second most important thing - Using Services</em></li>\n<li>Also some small tricky things I did not know…</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The more about each <em>my learning</em> you can learn <a href="https://github.com/aibolik/Sunshine/commits/master">here</a>, by reading each commit message and browsing <a href="https://github.com/aibolik/Sunshine">repo</a>.</p>'}}}]}},pathContext:{slug:"udacity-android-course-recap"}}}});
